Predicting human B cell extraction origin.¶

In this notebook, we will try to use scRNA-seq data to predict the tissue from which each cell was extracted.
The dataset was downloaded from the Tabula Sapiens Consortium.
In particular, this datasets origins from the paper of Suo et al., 2022, Science

A - Data analysis and Preprocessing¶

def get_annotated_chunk(ad_object, size=1024, row_memory=set()):
    all_rows = set(range(ad_object.X.shape[0]))
    possible_rows = list(all_rows - row_memory)

    ids = rd.sample(possible_rows, size)

    Xchunk = pd.DataFrame(ad_object.chunk_X(select=ids, replace=False), columns=ad_object.var_names)
    Xchunk.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    Ychunk = pd.DataFrame(ad_object.obs['tissue'].iloc[ids], columns=['tissue'])
    Ychunk.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

    return pd.concat([Xchunk, Ychunk], axis=1), ids

df, ids_1 = get_annotated_chunk(dataset_AnnData)

def plot_random_genes(df, n_genes=5, specify=None):
    genes = rd.sample(list(df.columns), n_genes) if specify is None else specify
    print("Selected genes:", genes)

    # Create a single row of subplots without sharing y-axis
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, len(genes), figsize=(5 * len(genes), 5), sharey=False)

    for i, gene in enumerate(genes):
        sns.histplot(df[gene], kde=True, ax=axes[i])
        axes[i].set_ylabel('Count')
        axes[i].set_xlabel('scRNA-seq Expression Level')
        axes[i].set_title(f'Distribution of Gene {gene}')
        
        # Optionally, set y-axis limits to start at 0 for clarity
        axes[i].set_ylim(bottom=0)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

A.2 - Dimensionality reduction¶

Too many genes, let's use dimensionality reduction techniques otherwise we will surely run into the curse of dimensionality.

The goal is to find a suitable method that better summarizes our data. We will test methods on our toy chunk of data.

def plot_data(df, target='tissue', dims=(0,1)):
    columns = list(df.columns)
    scatt = sns.scatterplot(data=df, x=columns[dims[0]], y=columns[dims[1]], hue=target)
    sns.move_legend(scatt, "upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

def get_embeddings(df, transformer, target={'tissue':-1}):
    transformed = transformer.fit_transform(df.iloc[:,:list(target.values())[0]])
    new_df = pd.DataFrame(transformed, columns=['Component ' + str(i) for i in range(transformed.shape[1])])
    new_df = pd.concat([new_df, df[list(target.keys())[0]]], axis=1)
    return new_df

It seems like, except for the thymus class, we are going to have difficulties seperating classes.

Another thing we can look for is genes that are never expressed, they could be removed from the feature matrix to reduce dimensionality. However to investigate this, we first need to quit using a toy chunk and actually define our dataset.

We could use 15 chunks of 1024 cells for training (15.360). 10 for validation and 10 for evaluation (so 10.240 cells each). The scale of those numbers justifies no cross-validation protocol being used in the training sections.

To help with memory usage, we will fit estimators on chunks of 1024.

In [21]:
def make_chunk_ids(ad_object, size=1024, row_memory=set()):
    all_rows = set(range(ad_object.X.shape[0]))
    possible_rows = list(all_rows - row_memory)

    ids = rd.sample(possible_rows, size)

    return ids

def get_chunk(ad_object, ids):
    Xchunk = pd.DataFrame(ad_object.chunk_X(select=ids, replace=False), columns=ad_object.var_names)
    Xchunk.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    Ychunk = pd.DataFrame(ad_object.obs['tissue'].iloc[ids], columns=['tissue'])
    Ychunk.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    return pd.concat([Xchunk, Ychunk], axis=1)

def make_sets(ad_object, train=15, val=10, test=10, size=1024):
    assert (train + val + test) * size <= ad_object.X.shape[0], "That would exceeds the number of available rows."
    sets = {'train':[], 'val':[], 'test':[]}
    memory = set()
    print('\n')
    for i in range(train):
        # print(f'Loading training chunk number {i+1}...')
        ids = make_chunk_ids(ad_object, size=size, row_memory=memory)
        memory.update(ids)
        sets['train'].append(ids)
    print('\n')
    for i in range(val):
        # print(f'Loading validation chunk number {i+1}...')
        ids = make_chunk_ids(ad_object, size=size, row_memory=memory)
        memory.update(ids)
        sets['val'].append(ids)
    print('\n')
    for i in range(test):
        # print(f'Loading test chunk number {i+1}...')
        ids = make_chunk_ids(ad_object, size=size, row_memory=memory)
        memory.update(ids)
        sets['test'].append(ids)
    return sets

The first thing to keep in mind is that the number of never expressed genes slightly varies depending on the training set composition (as we randomly select observation for each chunk). We could also set a threshold of minimum observations needed to consider the gene, however, some tissues are extremely rare with sometime None to 1 observations per chunk. So to correctly identify a suitable threshold, we need to determine the minimum number of observations for a class in our dataset. The threshold will necessarily be below that value.

How can we set this threshold ? One idea is to say that if less than 5% of the minimum number of class observations have this gene expressed then we can consider it as almost never expressed. The rationale behind this is that even if, all the observations where this gene is expressed were of the same class, and even if it was the less present class of the dataset, less than 5% means that it is not at all a representative gene for this class, thus we can suppose that other genes might be more useful to identify this class.

    chunk = get_chunk(dataset_AnnData, ids=id_list)

    else:
        S += np.sum(binary_chunk, axis=0)
        classes_counts += chunk['tissue'].value_counts()

Little to no changes are observed so, as expected, removing never expressed genes does not alter data structure !

As we cannot use the 25.000 + genes all at once, we need to rely on the embeddings of such techniques. However, one type of embedding may not capture all necessary informations as they use different assumptions and methods to reduce dimensionality.
Thus I will be using the embeddings of PCA and UMAP as input features of future ML models. PCA should provide a representation of linear correlations in the dataset and UMAP should provide non-linear ones.

To ensure consistent transformations between chunks, we will fit each technique on a subset of the training set and then use the trained dimensionality reductions models for validation and test chunks.

def ready_chunk(ad_object, ids):
    chunk = get_clean_chunk(ad_object, ids)
    chunk = chunk[training_features+['tissue']]
    pca_emb = pd.DataFrame(pca_model.transform(chunk.iloc[:,:-1]), columns=['PCA1', 'PCA2'])
    umap_emb = pd.DataFrame(umap_model.transform(chunk.iloc[:,:-1]), columns=['UMAP1', 'UMAP2'])
    return pd.concat([pca_emb, umap_emb, chunk['tissue']], axis=1)

A normalization step will be useful for some models we will try in the following section. We want to make sure that no feature gets assigned more importance simply due to its scale of values so let's apply a feature-wise noramlization step. We will not assume anything about the distribution of our features so we will be using MinMaxScaler. Another useful step is to convert classes to integers, it will make chunks slightly lighter and will be more suitable for model training and testing.

In [37]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
translator = {tissue:i for i,tissue in enumerate(labels)}
reverse_translator = {i:key for i,key in enumerate(translator.keys())}

def norm_ready_chunk(ad_object, ids):
    chunk = ready_chunk(ad_object, ids)
    norm_X = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(chunk.iloc[:,:-1]), columns=chunk.columns[:-1])
    chunk['tissue'] = chunk['tissue'].map(translator)
    return pd.concat([norm_X, chunk['tissue']], axis=1)

B - Models¶

Our baseline model for this problem will be a RidgeClassifier. Then we will compare with a LinearSVC, a RandomForestClassifier and CatBoostClassifier. This will allow us to compare a variety of approaches and find the best one for the task at hand.

Howerever, we mentioned the highly unbalanced nature of our data. This requires a little thinking into how we evaluate our models. To correctly evaluate them we will be using the f1_score function which combines precision and recall. Computing weight classes is also necessary to take into account the unbalanced nature of the dataset.

In [39]:

def get_sets_data(ad_object, sets, normalize=True):
    dico = {}

    for key in ['train', 'val', 'test']:
        print(f'\nStarted gathering chunks for {key}.')
        chunk_list = []
        for i,id_list in enumerate(sets[key]):
            chunk = norm_ready_chunk(ad_object, id_list) if normalize else ready_chunk(ad_object, id_list)
            chunk_list.append(chunk)
        df = pd.concat(chunk_list, axis=0)
        print(f'\nRetrieved all chunks, data shape is {df.shape}')
        dico.update({key:df})
    return dico

def train_model(estimator, training_data, target='tissue'):
    columns = list(training_data.columns)
    if target in columns :
        columns.remove(target)
        
    print('\nStarted training..')
    estimator.fit(training_data[columns], training_data[target])
    print(f'\nTraining ended.')
    return estimator

def validate_model(estimator, val_data, tag, target='tissue', show_cm=False):
    columns = list(val_data.columns)
    if target in columns :
        columns.remove(target)

    y_hat = estimator.predict(val_data[columns])
    y_true = val_data[target]

    global_perf = f1_score(y_true, y_hat, average='micro')
    
    if show_cm:
        plt.figure()
        ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_true, y_hat, 
                                                labels=estimator.classes_, 
                                                display_labels=[reverse_translator[key] for key in estimator.classes_],
                                                normalize='true',
                                                values_format='.2f',
                                                xticks_rotation='vertical')
        plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix for {tag[0]} on {tag[1]} set.')
        plt.show()
    print(f'Overall F1 score : {global_perf}')
    w_perf = f1_score(y_true, y_hat, average='weighted')
    print(f'Weighted F1 score :', w_perf)
    return global_perf, w_perf

def compare_models(models_dict, ad_object, sets_dico, normalize=True, target='tissue'):
    val_results = {model_name:0 for model_name in models_dict.keys()}
    train_results = {model_name:0 for model_name in models_dict.keys()}

    for model_name in models_dict.keys():
        print(f'\nTraining {model_name}..')
        model = models_dict[model_name]
        fitted_model = train_model(model, sets_dico['train'], target=target)

        print('\nEvaluation on training set..')
        _ , perf = validate_model(fitted_model, sets_dico['train'], tag=(model_name, 'training'), target=target)
        train_results[model_name] = perf

        print('\nEvaluation on Validation set..')
        _ , perf = validate_model(fitted_model, sets_dico['val'], tag=(model_name, 'validation'), target=target)
        val_results[model_name] = perf
    return train_results, val_results

def plot_model_performances(train_results, val_results):
    dico = {'Model':list(train_results.keys())+list(val_results.keys()), 
            'Weighted F1 score':list(train_results.values())+list(val_results.values()),
            'Set':['train']*len(list(train_results.keys())) + ['val']*len(list(train_results.keys()))
            }
    df = pd.DataFrame(dico)
    print(df)
    sns.barplot(data=df, x='Model', y='Weighted F1 score', hue='Set', palette='viridis')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

C - Model Optimization¶

In this section we will try to improve performances using hyperparameter tuning and feature selection.

C.1 - Feature Selection¶

First things first, we can try to see if a subset of our embedding features can be sufficient to obtain same level performances or even better ones.

In [46]:
def select_features(estimator, training_data, val_data, target='tissue', min_improvement=1e-4):
    columns = list(training_data.columns)
    columns.remove(target)
    perf_history = []
    old_perf = -np.inf
    perf = 0
    n_features = 1
    kept = []
    best_model = None
    while perf >= old_perf + min_improvement:
        # Create combinations of features
        combinations = [kept + [col] for col in columns if col not in kept]

        if combinations == []:
            break
        # For each combination we train and evaluate the model
        perf_list = []
        model_list = []
        for comb in combinations:
            print(comb)
            fitted_model = train_model(estimator, training_data[comb+[target]])
            print('\nEvaluation on validation set..')
            _ , new_perf = validate_model(fitted_model, val_data[comb+[target]], tag=('CatBoostClassifier', 'val'), target=target)
            perf_list.append(new_perf)
            model_list.append(fitted_model)
            perf_history.append((comb, new_perf))
        # We take the best performance and update the performance threshold
        old_perf = perf
        perf = np.max(perf_list)
        
        if perf > old_perf:
            # We update the best combination of features and model accordingly
            best_comb = combinations[np.argmax(perf_list)]
            kept = best_comb
            best_model = model_list[np.argmax(perf_list)]
        # We look for combinations of n+1 features
        n_features += 1
    return best_comb, best_model, perf_history

def plot_feature_selection(perf_history):
    dico = {'Features':[str(t[0]) for t in perf_history],
            'Weighted F1 score': [t[1] for t in perf_history]}
    df = pd.DataFrame(dico)
    plt.figure()
    ax = sns.barplot(data=df, y='Features', x='Weighted F1 score', palette='viridis', orient='h')
    for bars in ax.containers:
        ax.bar_label(bars)
    ax.set_xlim((0,1.1))
    plt.show()

In [49]:
def add_interactions(data, target='tissue'):
    columns = list(data.columns)
    columns.remove(target)

    dico = {}
    for col1 in columns:
        for col2 in columns:
            if col1 != col2:
                name = col1[0] + col1[-1] + 'x' + col2[0] + col2[-1]
                alt_name = col2[0] + col2[-1] + 'x' + col1[0] + col1[-1]
                if name not in dico.keys() and alt_name not in dico.keys() :
                    dico.update({name:np.array(data[col1]) * np.array(data[col2])})
    
    df = pd.DataFrame(dico)
    data.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    return pd.concat([data[columns], df, data[target]], axis=1)

C.2 - Hyperparameter tuning¶

Now that we know that we cannot hope for better performances with this given set of features, we'll try to optimize the model's performances using hyperparameter tuning.

In [52]:
%%capture
import optuna

def objective(trial):
    n_estimators = trial.suggest_int("n_estimators", 10, 200)
    max_depth = trial.suggest_int("max_depth", 15, 25)
    criterion = trial.suggest_categorical("criterion", ['gini','entropy','log_loss'])
    min_samples_split = trial.suggest_int("min_samples_split", 2, 6)
    min_samples_leaf = trial.suggest_int("min_samples_leaf", 1, 6)
    max_features = trial.suggest_categorical("max_features", ["sqrt", "log2", None])
    class_weight = trial.suggest_categorical("class_weight", [class_weight_dico]) 

    model = RandomForestClassifier(
        n_estimators=n_estimators,
        max_depth=max_depth,
        criterion=criterion,
        min_samples_split=min_samples_split,
        min_samples_leaf=min_samples_leaf,
        max_features=max_features,
        class_weight=class_weight,
        n_jobs=-1,
        random_state=42
    )

    fitted_model = train_model(model, train_data_w_interactions[best_comb+['tissue']], target='tissue')

    _ , perf = validate_model(fitted_model, val_data_w_interactions[best_comb+['tissue']], target='tissue', tag=('RandomForestClassifier', 'val'))
    
    return perf


study = optuna.create_study(direction="maximize")
study.optimize(objective, n_trials=20)

Overall F1 score : 0.78466796875

What we can see is that our model essentially learned to detect the 3 predominant tissues in the dataset : thymus, liver and bone marrow. This was to be expected as the dataset was very unbalanced towards those tissues. However we also could have expected better results because of the use of class weights and weighted F1 metric.

Strategies we could have used to increase model performance are :

  • We can see that yolk sac and gut wall are often mis-predicted as liver. kidney bound cells are often mis-predicted as bone marrow. It could be interesting to ask experts if there are known factors which could help differenciate these tissues. If so, we could use these factors or set of factors with current features to make predictions.

  • Using resampling methods to make sure each set has balanced classes distributions, however this would have significantly reduced the number of samples we could use for training which could also be a limiting factor for performance increase.

  • Instead of solely relying on embeddings, we could have explored the interactions between genes (matrix of all possible pair-wise products between gene features) and then try to identify if certain interactions were more significant. We could have then used dimensionality reduction techniques on the interaction matrix aswell. However due to the size of the data, this would have required access to GPUs and more time which both lacked.

  • Finally we also could use Neural Networks for such a task, as the embedding space representation revealed that a lot of classes were overlapping, the task of correctly predicting all 9 tissues with such unbalanceness may require more descriptive power.
